1
00:00:01,418 --> 00:00:04,171
DOCTOR: The library.
So big it doesn't need a name.

2
00:00:04,254 --> 00:00:06,673
Someone's got in.
Someone's in my library.

3
00:00:06,757 --> 00:00:09,843
"4,022 saved. No survivors."

4
00:00:09,927 --> 00:00:12,471
-Others are coming.
-What others?

5
00:00:18,477 --> 00:00:21,230
Professor River Song. Archaeologist.

6
00:00:21,438 --> 00:00:22,981
You've seen me before, then?

7
00:00:23,190 --> 00:00:27,569
The real world is a lie,
and your nightmares are real.

8
00:00:28,820 --> 00:00:30,030
What's CAL?

9
00:00:30,113 --> 00:00:33,575
The library is real.
There are people trapped in there.

10
00:00:33,659 --> 00:00:35,869
People who need to be saved.

11
00:00:35,953 --> 00:00:37,996
There's a neural relay
in the communicator.

12
00:00:38,121 --> 00:00:41,083
Sometimes it can hold an impression
of a living consciousness

13
00:00:41,166 --> 00:00:42,793
for a short time after death.

14
00:00:43,001 --> 00:00:46,338
The shadows are moving again.
Only you can save them.

15
00:00:46,421 --> 00:00:49,132
The piranhas of the air.
The Vashta Nerada.

16
00:00:49,258 --> 00:00:50,676
(SCREAMING)

17
00:00:52,302 --> 00:00:54,471
Donna Noble has been saved.

18
00:00:54,555 --> 00:00:56,348
Donna Noble has been saved.

19
00:00:56,473 --> 00:00:57,891
Hey, who turned out the lights?

20
00:00:57,975 --> 00:01:01,895
Donna Noble has left the library.
Donna Noble has been saved.

21
00:01:01,979 --> 00:01:03,397
Hey, who turned out the lights?

22
00:01:03,480 --> 00:01:06,066
Donna Noble has left the library.
Donna Noble has been saved.

23
00:01:06,149 --> 00:01:08,026
Hey, who turned out the lights?

24
00:01:08,151 --> 00:01:12,906
Donna Noble has left the library.
Donna Noble has been saved.

25
00:01:15,325 --> 00:01:17,953
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

26
00:01:54,156 --> 00:01:56,366
Hey, who turned out the lights?

27
00:01:57,117 --> 00:01:58,744
Hey, who turned out the lights?

28
00:02:00,829 --> 00:02:02,623
This way, quickly! Move!

29
00:02:03,707 --> 00:02:05,542
Hey, who turned out the lights?

30
00:02:05,917 --> 00:02:09,212
Dad, the library,
it's on television now.

31
00:02:09,338 --> 00:02:14,092
How many times, darling?
The library is just your imagination.

32
00:02:47,918 --> 00:02:49,127
Donna?

33
00:02:58,345 --> 00:02:59,888
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

34
00:03:03,433 --> 00:03:05,352
Hello, Donna.

35
00:03:05,435 --> 00:03:07,854
-Who are you?
-I'm Dr Moon.

36
00:03:08,730 --> 00:03:12,651
I've been treating you
since you came here two years ago.

37
00:03:12,734 --> 00:03:16,488
Oh, God. Dr Moon, I'm so sorry.

38
00:03:17,155 --> 00:03:20,909
What's wrong with me?
I didn't know you for a moment.

39
00:03:21,034 --> 00:03:23,120
And then you remembered.

40
00:03:23,662 --> 00:03:27,290
Shall we go for a walk?
No more dreams, then?

41
00:03:27,374 --> 00:03:30,961
The Doctor, the blue box,
time and space.

42
00:03:32,671 --> 00:03:34,756
How did we get here?

43
00:03:35,590 --> 00:03:38,885
We came down the stairs,
out the front door.

44
00:03:38,969 --> 00:03:41,471
We passed Mrs Ali on the way out.

45
00:03:42,597 --> 00:03:44,975
Yeah. Yeah, we did.

46
00:03:46,101 --> 00:03:48,645
-I forgot that.
-And then you remembered.

47
00:03:51,356 --> 00:03:54,109
Shall we go down to the river?

48
00:03:54,192 --> 00:03:57,863
You said "river"”
and suddenly we're feeding ducks.

49
00:03:57,988 --> 00:03:59,823
Dr Moon.

50
00:04:01,074 --> 00:04:02,576
Morning.

51
00:04:02,659 --> 00:04:05,162
Donna Noble, Lee McAvoy.

52
00:04:06,788 --> 00:04:08,707
-Hello, Lee.
-Hello.

53
00:04:11,209 --> 00:04:13,295
Ooh, you've got
a bit of a stammer there.

54
00:04:13,378 --> 00:04:14,796
Bless.

55
00:04:15,547 --> 00:04:17,174
(LEE STAMMERING)

56
00:04:17,299 --> 00:04:19,551
Oh, skip to a vowel, they're easy.

57
00:04:20,677 --> 00:04:23,013
How did we leave it, him and me?

58
00:04:23,138 --> 00:04:27,017
I got the impression
he was inviting you fishing. Tomorrow.

59
00:04:30,312 --> 00:04:31,521
So...

60
00:04:33,398 --> 00:04:34,858
Fishing?

61
00:04:34,941 --> 00:04:36,860
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

62
00:04:38,445 --> 00:04:39,946
(STAMMERING)

63
00:04:41,448 --> 00:04:43,825
Gorgeous, and can't speak a word.

64
00:04:45,452 --> 00:04:47,788
What am I gonna do with you?

65
00:04:47,871 --> 00:04:51,291
(STAMMERING) Welcome home, Mrs McAvoy.

66
00:04:54,294 --> 00:04:56,463
(CHILDREN SQUEALING)

67
00:04:56,546 --> 00:05:00,008
Stop it. Stop it now.
We've got a visitor.

68
00:05:00,091 --> 00:05:02,886
You've done so much
in seven years, Donna.

69
00:05:02,969 --> 00:05:05,388
Sometimes it feels more like 70.

70
00:05:06,223 --> 00:05:09,309
Mind you, sometimes
it feels like no time at all.

71
00:05:11,812 --> 00:05:16,066
Can I just say what a pleasure it is
to see you fully integrated?

72
00:05:19,236 --> 00:05:21,947
DOCTOR: The signal's definitely
coming from the moon.

73
00:05:22,072 --> 00:05:25,367
I'm blocking it, but it's trying to
break through. Donna!

74
00:05:25,450 --> 00:05:27,452
Oops, sorry.

75
00:05:27,577 --> 00:05:29,955
Mrs Angelo's rhubarb surprise.

76
00:05:30,080 --> 00:05:31,832
Will I never learn?

77
00:05:33,250 --> 00:05:34,668
The Doctor!

78
00:05:35,335 --> 00:05:37,128
I saw the Doctor!

79
00:05:37,254 --> 00:05:41,007
Yes, you did, Donna,
and then you forgot.

80
00:05:43,468 --> 00:05:46,930
Dr Moon. Oh, hello.

81
00:05:47,055 --> 00:05:49,432
Shall I make you a cup of tea?

82
00:06:02,863 --> 00:06:04,990
(ELECTRONIC BUZZING)

83
00:06:08,285 --> 00:06:11,413
Okay, we got a clear spot. In, in, in!

84
00:06:11,496 --> 00:06:14,082
Right in the centre,
in the middle of the light. Quickly!

85
00:06:14,165 --> 00:06:15,834
Don't let your shadows cross.

86
00:06:15,917 --> 00:06:17,752
-Doctor...
-I'm doing it.

87
00:06:17,836 --> 00:06:19,796
There's no light here.

88
00:06:19,880 --> 00:06:22,549
Sunset's coming. We can't stay long.

89
00:06:23,842 --> 00:06:25,510
Have you found a live one?

90
00:06:25,594 --> 00:06:29,055
Maybe, it's getting harder to tell.
What's wrong with you?

91
00:06:29,139 --> 00:06:32,684
We're going to need a chicken leg.
Who's got a chicken leg?

92
00:06:32,809 --> 00:06:34,311
Thanks, Dave.

93
00:06:39,232 --> 00:06:42,527
Okay. Okay, we got a hot one.
Watch your feet.

94
00:06:42,652 --> 00:06:44,988
They won't attack
until there's enough of them.

95
00:06:45,071 --> 00:06:47,991
But they've got our scent now.
They're coming.

96
00:06:49,451 --> 00:06:51,244
River, who is he?

97
00:06:51,328 --> 00:06:54,623
You haven't even told us.
You just expect us to trust him.

98
00:06:54,706 --> 00:06:56,374
He's the Doctor.

99
00:06:56,499 --> 00:06:58,835
And who is "The Doctor"?

100
00:06:58,919 --> 00:07:03,340
The only story you'll ever tell,
if you survive him.

101
00:07:03,506 --> 00:07:07,093
You say he's your friend,
but he doesn't even know who you are.

102
00:07:07,177 --> 00:07:09,054
Listen, all you need to know is this,

103
00:07:09,179 --> 00:07:11,348
I trust that man
to the end of the universe.

104
00:07:11,431 --> 00:07:13,516
And actually, we've been.

105
00:07:16,937 --> 00:07:19,022
He doesn't act like he trusts you.

106
00:07:19,105 --> 00:07:21,691
Yeah. There's a tiny problem.

107
00:07:21,775 --> 00:07:23,652
He hasn't met me yet.

108
00:07:29,199 --> 00:07:32,285
-What's wrong with it?
-There's a signal coming from somewhere.

109
00:07:32,369 --> 00:07:35,288
-Interfering with it.
-Well, use the red settings.

110
00:07:35,372 --> 00:07:38,124
-It doesn't have a red setting.
-Well, use the dampers.

111
00:07:38,208 --> 00:07:41,378
-It doesn't have dampers.
-It will do one day.

112
00:07:44,798 --> 00:07:47,717
So, sometime in the future,
I just give you my screwdriver?

113
00:07:47,801 --> 00:07:50,095
-Yeah.
-Why would I do that?

114
00:07:50,220 --> 00:07:51,846
I didn't pluck it
from your cold, dead hands

115
00:07:51,930 --> 00:07:53,431
if that's what you're worried about.

116
00:07:53,556 --> 00:07:55,642
And I know that because...?

117
00:07:55,725 --> 00:07:59,312
Listen to me, you've lost your friend,
you're angry, I understand.

118
00:07:59,396 --> 00:08:01,773
But you need to be less emotional,
Doctor, right now...

119
00:08:01,856 --> 00:08:03,525
Less... I'm not emotional.

120
00:08:03,608 --> 00:08:07,237
There are five people in this room
still alive. Focus on that.

121
00:08:07,320 --> 00:08:10,490
-Dear God, you're hard work young.
-Young? Who are you?

122
00:08:10,573 --> 00:08:13,159
Oh, for heaven's sake!
Look at the pair of you!

123
00:08:13,243 --> 00:08:14,786
We're all going to die right here,

124
00:08:14,869 --> 00:08:18,540
and you're just squabbling
like an old married couple.

125
00:08:21,543 --> 00:08:22,877
Doctor,

126
00:08:24,087 --> 00:08:26,548
one day, I'm going to be
someone that you trust.

127
00:08:26,631 --> 00:08:28,550
Completely.

128
00:08:28,633 --> 00:08:32,137
But I can't wait for you
to find that out.

129
00:08:32,262 --> 00:08:34,973
So I'm going to prove it to you.

130
00:08:35,098 --> 00:08:36,599
And I'm sorry.

131
00:08:38,893 --> 00:08:41,521
I'm really very sorry.

132
00:08:54,325 --> 00:08:55,827
Are we good?

133
00:08:57,829 --> 00:09:00,623
Doctor, are we good?

134
00:09:03,043 --> 00:09:04,210
Yeah.

135
00:09:05,462 --> 00:09:07,172
Yeah, we're good.

136
00:09:11,176 --> 00:09:12,343
Good.

137
00:09:21,102 --> 00:09:23,021
Now, what's interesting
about my screwdriver,

138
00:09:23,104 --> 00:09:25,857
very hard to interfere with.
Practically nothing's strong enough.

139
00:09:25,982 --> 00:09:27,734
Well, some hair dryers,
but I'm working on that.

140
00:09:27,817 --> 00:09:30,570
So, there is a very strong signal
coming from somewhere,

141
00:09:30,653 --> 00:09:34,449
and it wasn't there before.
So, what's new? What's changed?

142
00:09:34,532 --> 00:09:36,701
Come on! What's new? What's different?

143
00:09:36,826 --> 00:09:39,162
I don't know. Nothing.

144
00:09:39,245 --> 00:09:41,039
It's getting dark.

145
00:09:41,122 --> 00:09:44,000
It's a screwdriver.
It works in the dark.

146
00:09:45,001 --> 00:09:46,336
Moonlight.

147
00:09:49,923 --> 00:09:51,758
Tell me about the moon. What's there?

148
00:09:51,841 --> 00:09:54,052
It's not real.
It was built as part of the library.

149
00:09:54,135 --> 00:09:56,221
-It's just a doctor moon.
-What's a doctor moon?

150
00:09:56,346 --> 00:09:57,430
A virus checker.

151
00:09:57,514 --> 00:10:01,017
It supports and maintains the main
computer at the core of the planet.

152
00:10:01,351 --> 00:10:04,813
Well, it's still active.
It's signalling, look.

153
00:10:05,396 --> 00:10:07,565
Someone somewhere
in this library is alive

154
00:10:07,690 --> 00:10:09,109
and communicating with the moon.

155
00:10:09,192 --> 00:10:12,195
Or possibly alive and drying their hair.

156
00:10:12,278 --> 00:10:16,199
No. Signal is definitely
coming from the moon.

157
00:10:16,282 --> 00:10:17,826
I'm blocking it,
but it's trying to break through.

158
00:10:17,909 --> 00:10:19,035
Doctor!

159
00:10:19,119 --> 00:10:20,328
Donna!

160
00:10:20,411 --> 00:10:22,372
Doctor, that was your friend.

161
00:10:22,455 --> 00:10:24,541
Can you get her back? What was that?

162
00:10:24,707 --> 00:10:28,419
Hold on, hold on, hold on.
Trying to find the wavelength.

163
00:10:28,503 --> 00:10:30,630
-Being blocked!
-Professor...

164
00:10:30,713 --> 00:10:33,424
-SONG: Just a moment.
-It's important.

165
00:10:34,634 --> 00:10:36,427
I have two shadows.

166
00:10:38,388 --> 00:10:41,558
Helmets on, everyone.
Anita, I'll get yours.

167
00:10:41,641 --> 00:10:43,852
Didn't do Proper Dave any good.

168
00:10:43,935 --> 00:10:46,437
Just keep it together, okay?

169
00:10:46,521 --> 00:10:48,690
Keeping it together.

170
00:10:48,773 --> 00:10:50,567
I'm only crying.

171
00:10:50,733 --> 00:10:53,695
I'm about to die,
it's not an overreaction.

172
00:10:58,575 --> 00:10:59,909
Hang on.

173
00:11:01,619 --> 00:11:05,707
-Oh, God, they've got inside.
-No, no. I just tinted her visor.

174
00:11:05,790 --> 00:11:08,334
Maybe they'll think they're already
in there. Leave her alone.

175
00:11:08,418 --> 00:11:10,253
You think they could be
fooled like that?

176
00:11:10,336 --> 00:11:13,840
Maybe, I don't know.
It's a swarm, it's not like we chat.

177
00:11:13,923 --> 00:11:15,383
Can you still see, Anita?

178
00:11:15,466 --> 00:11:19,053
-Just about.
-Just stay back.

179
00:11:19,137 --> 00:11:21,055
-Professor, quick word please.
-What?

180
00:11:21,139 --> 00:11:23,183
-Down here.
-What is it?

181
00:11:23,266 --> 00:11:26,019
You said there are five people
still alive in this room.

182
00:11:26,102 --> 00:11:27,770
-Yeah, so?
-So...

183
00:11:29,522 --> 00:11:31,274
Why are there six?

184
00:11:35,403 --> 00:11:37,113
Hey, who turned out the lights?

185
00:11:37,238 --> 00:11:38,448
Run!

186
00:11:39,574 --> 00:11:42,035
Hey, who turned out the lights?

187
00:11:45,914 --> 00:11:48,333
ON TV: Hey, who turned out the lights?

188
00:11:48,958 --> 00:11:50,585
Hey, who turned out the lights?

189
00:11:50,668 --> 00:11:53,463
-Here you are, Dr Moon.
-Mummy, I made you!

190
00:11:53,546 --> 00:11:56,799
Ooh. That's nice, Ella.
Where's the face?

191
00:11:56,925 --> 00:11:58,426
I don't know.

192
00:11:59,344 --> 00:12:02,222
Did you see Dr Moon? Did he leave?

193
00:12:02,305 --> 00:12:04,224
-KIDS: Daddy!
-Hey, hello, kids!

194
00:12:04,307 --> 00:12:07,393
Come here, big hugs. Big Daddy hugs!

195
00:12:07,477 --> 00:12:08,603
Look what I made.

196
00:12:08,686 --> 00:12:12,023
-Oh! It's Mummy.
-It hasn't got a face.

197
00:12:12,106 --> 00:12:14,442
-Did you see Dr Moon?
-No. Why, was he here?

198
00:12:14,525 --> 00:12:17,904
Yeah, just a second ago.
You must have passed him.

199
00:12:21,324 --> 00:12:23,493
You all right?

200
00:12:23,618 --> 00:12:24,786
Yeah.

201
00:12:25,536 --> 00:12:28,706
-Yeah, I'm fine. It's just...
-Just?

202
00:12:31,167 --> 00:12:32,460
Nothing.

203
00:12:35,255 --> 00:12:38,341
It's been a long day, that's all.

204
00:12:38,466 --> 00:12:39,676
Just tired.

205
00:12:42,845 --> 00:12:44,514
You okay?

206
00:12:44,597 --> 00:12:46,975
I said I was tired

207
00:12:47,058 --> 00:12:48,518
and...

208
00:12:49,435 --> 00:12:53,189
And we put the kids to bed,
and we watched television.

209
00:12:54,190 --> 00:12:55,650
(RATTLING)

210
00:12:56,317 --> 00:12:57,694
Is that a letter?

211
00:12:57,819 --> 00:13:00,321
-It's midnight.
-Go see what it is.

212
00:13:17,463 --> 00:13:19,549
LEE: The world is wrong.

213
00:13:19,632 --> 00:13:22,510
-What?
-For you. Weird, though.

214
00:13:22,593 --> 00:13:26,055
"Dear Donna, the world is wrong.

215
00:13:26,139 --> 00:13:29,434
"Meet me at your usual play park,
2:00 tomorrow."

216
00:13:41,321 --> 00:13:42,488
Nutter.

217
00:13:46,242 --> 00:13:48,453
Don't go! Please don't go!

218
00:13:56,586 --> 00:13:59,088
All right, you two, off you go.
No fighting.

219
00:13:59,172 --> 00:14:00,923
(CHILDREN GIGGLING)

220
00:14:21,069 --> 00:14:23,696
I got your note last night.

221
00:14:23,780 --> 00:14:25,615
"The world is wrong."
What does that mean?

222
00:14:25,698 --> 00:14:28,242
-No, you didn't.
-I'm sorry, what?

223
00:14:28,326 --> 00:14:30,703
You didn't get my note last night.

224
00:14:30,787 --> 00:14:33,373
You got it a few seconds ago.

225
00:14:33,456 --> 00:14:37,835
Having decided to come,
you suddenly found yourself arriving.

226
00:14:37,960 --> 00:14:41,756
That is how time progresses here,
in the manner of a dream.

227
00:14:41,839 --> 00:14:45,510
You've suspected that before,
haven't you, Donna Noble?

228
00:14:47,637 --> 00:14:51,474
-How do you know me?
-We met before. In the library.

229
00:14:52,475 --> 00:14:54,352
You were kind to me.

230
00:14:54,435 --> 00:14:57,063
I hope now to return that kindness.

231
00:14:59,273 --> 00:15:00,733
Your voice...

232
00:15:02,276 --> 00:15:04,654
-I recognise it.
-Yes, you do.

233
00:15:06,030 --> 00:15:08,783
I am what is left of Miss Evangelista.

234
00:15:20,586 --> 00:15:22,505
Professor, go ahead. Find a safe spot.

235
00:15:22,588 --> 00:15:25,174
It's a carnivorous swarm in a suit.
You can't reason with it.

236
00:15:25,258 --> 00:15:26,634
Five minutes.

237
00:15:26,717 --> 00:15:29,762
Other Dave, stay with him. Pull him out
when he's too stupid to live.

238
00:15:29,846 --> 00:15:31,722
Two minutes, Doctor.

239
00:15:33,307 --> 00:15:34,767
Hey, who turned out the lights?

240
00:15:34,851 --> 00:15:36,853
You hear that? Those words?

241
00:15:36,936 --> 00:15:39,522
That is the very last thought
of the man who wore that suit,

242
00:15:39,605 --> 00:15:43,025
before you climbed inside
and stripped his flesh.

243
00:15:43,192 --> 00:15:44,485
That's a man's soul

244
00:15:44,569 --> 00:15:47,530
trapped inside a neural relay,
going round and round forever.

245
00:15:47,613 --> 00:15:50,408
Now, if you don't have the decency
to let him go, how about this?

246
00:15:50,533 --> 00:15:52,660
Use him, talk to me.

247
00:15:53,911 --> 00:15:57,623
It's easy. Neural relay. Just point
and think. Use him, talk to me.

248
00:15:57,707 --> 00:15:59,876
Hey, who turned out the lights?

249
00:15:59,959 --> 00:16:02,128
The Vashta Nerada
live on all the worlds in this system,

250
00:16:02,211 --> 00:16:05,173
but you hunt in forests.
What are you doing in a library?

251
00:16:05,256 --> 00:16:07,049
-We should go. Doctor!
-In a minute.

252
00:16:07,133 --> 00:16:10,636
You came to a library to hunt.
Why? Just tell me why.

253
00:16:16,100 --> 00:16:18,311
We did not...

254
00:16:18,728 --> 00:16:20,480
Oh, hello.

255
00:16:21,439 --> 00:16:23,441
We did not...

256
00:16:23,524 --> 00:16:27,069
Take it easy, you'll get the hang of it.
Did not what?

257
00:16:27,153 --> 00:16:30,740
We did not come here.

258
00:16:30,823 --> 00:16:33,201
Well, of course you did.
Of course you came here.

259
00:16:33,284 --> 00:16:35,661
We come from here.

260
00:16:36,537 --> 00:16:37,580
From here?

261
00:16:37,747 --> 00:16:39,749
We hatched here.

262
00:16:39,832 --> 00:16:42,335
You hatch from trees,
from spores in trees.

263
00:16:42,418 --> 00:16:46,589
These are our forests.

264
00:16:46,756 --> 00:16:49,008
You're nowhere near a forest.
Look around you.

265
00:16:49,091 --> 00:16:52,595
These are our forests.

266
00:16:52,678 --> 00:16:55,723
You're not in a forest.
You're in a library.

267
00:16:55,806 --> 00:16:57,934
There are no trees in a...

268
00:16:58,726 --> 00:17:02,146
-Library.
-We should go. Doctor!

269
00:17:02,271 --> 00:17:05,149
Books. You came in the books.

270
00:17:08,569 --> 00:17:11,864
Microspores in a million, million books.

271
00:17:11,948 --> 00:17:15,785
-We should go. Doctor!
-Oh! Look at that!

272
00:17:15,868 --> 00:17:18,621
The forest of the Vashta Nerada,

273
00:17:18,746 --> 00:17:21,123
pulped and printed and bound.

274
00:17:22,166 --> 00:17:25,878
A million, million books
hatching shadows.

275
00:17:25,962 --> 00:17:28,089
We should go. Doctor!

276
00:17:30,174 --> 00:17:33,135
Oh, Dave!

277
00:17:33,219 --> 00:17:35,221
Oh, Dave, I'm so sorry!

278
00:17:37,098 --> 00:17:39,767
-Hey, who turned out the lights?
-We should go. Doctor!

279
00:17:39,850 --> 00:17:41,435
Thing about me, I'm stupid.
I talk too much.

280
00:17:41,519 --> 00:17:43,312
I was babbling on.
This gob doesn't stop for anything.

281
00:17:43,396 --> 00:17:46,315
Want to know the only reason
I'm still alive?

282
00:17:46,440 --> 00:17:48,526
Always stay near the door.

283
00:18:08,629 --> 00:18:10,590
EVANGELISTA: I suggested we meet here

284
00:18:10,673 --> 00:18:13,593
because the playground's
the easiest place to see it.

285
00:18:13,676 --> 00:18:15,845
-To see the lie.
-What lie?

286
00:18:16,512 --> 00:18:19,056
The children. Look at the children.

287
00:18:19,682 --> 00:18:22,143
Why do you wear that veil?

288
00:18:22,226 --> 00:18:24,604
If I had a face like yours,
I wouldn't hide it.

289
00:18:24,687 --> 00:18:26,814
You remember my face, then?

290
00:18:29,108 --> 00:18:31,110
The memories are all still there.

291
00:18:31,193 --> 00:18:34,071
The library, the Doctor, me.

292
00:18:34,155 --> 00:18:37,033
You've just been programmed not to look.

293
00:18:38,951 --> 00:18:41,329
Sorry, but you're dead.

294
00:18:42,163 --> 00:18:44,832
In a way we're all dead here, Donna.

295
00:18:44,915 --> 00:18:47,335
We are the dead of the library.

296
00:18:48,461 --> 00:18:51,297
Well, what about the children?
The children aren't dead.

297
00:18:51,380 --> 00:18:54,800
-My children aren't dead.
-Your children were never alive.

298
00:18:54,884 --> 00:18:56,677
Don't you say that.

299
00:18:56,761 --> 00:18:58,554
Don't you dare say that
about my children!

300
00:18:58,679 --> 00:19:00,348
Look at your children.

301
00:19:00,431 --> 00:19:04,143
Look at all of them, really look.
They're not real.

302
00:19:04,226 --> 00:19:06,896
Do you see it now? They're all the same.

303
00:19:09,065 --> 00:19:11,984
All the children of this world,
the same boy and the same girl,

304
00:19:12,068 --> 00:19:14,070
over and over again.

305
00:19:14,195 --> 00:19:17,740
Stop it! Just stop it!
Why are you doing this?

306
00:19:17,823 --> 00:19:20,117
Why are you wearing that veil?

307
00:19:43,015 --> 00:19:45,226
You know,

308
00:19:45,309 --> 00:19:47,895
it's funny,
I keep wishing the Doctor was here.

309
00:19:47,978 --> 00:19:50,606
ANITA: The Doctor is here, isn't he?

310
00:19:50,731 --> 00:19:52,733
He's coming back, right?

311
00:19:56,278 --> 00:19:58,656
You know when you see a photograph
of someone you know,

312
00:19:58,739 --> 00:20:02,118
but it's from years
before you knew them?

313
00:20:02,284 --> 00:20:06,414
It's like they're not quite finished.
They're not done yet.

314
00:20:07,373 --> 00:20:11,585
Well, yes, the Doctor's here.

315
00:20:12,294 --> 00:20:15,589
He came when I called,
just like he always does.

316
00:20:16,590 --> 00:20:19,385
But not my Doctor.

317
00:20:23,222 --> 00:20:24,807
Now, my Doctor...

318
00:20:27,143 --> 00:20:29,437
I've seen whole armies

319
00:20:29,520 --> 00:20:32,064
turn and run away,

320
00:20:32,148 --> 00:20:36,902
and he'd just swagger off
back to his Tardis

321
00:20:36,986 --> 00:20:40,156
and open the doors
with a snap of his fingers.

322
00:20:42,199 --> 00:20:45,453
The Doctor, in the Tardis.

323
00:20:46,662 --> 00:20:48,706
Next stop everywhere.

324
00:20:48,789 --> 00:20:50,541
DOCTOR: Spoilers.

325
00:20:53,169 --> 00:20:56,881
Nobody can open a Tardis
by snapping their fingers.

326
00:20:56,964 --> 00:21:00,176
-Doesn't work like that.
-It does for the Doctor.

327
00:21:00,259 --> 00:21:03,596
-I am the Doctor.
-Yeah. Someday.

328
00:21:06,932 --> 00:21:09,101
-How you doing?
-Where's Other Dave?

329
00:21:09,185 --> 00:21:10,978
Not coming, sorry.

330
00:21:12,646 --> 00:21:15,775
Well, if they've taken him,
why haven't they gotten me yet?

331
00:21:15,858 --> 00:21:17,693
I don't know.

332
00:21:17,818 --> 00:21:20,029
Maybe tinting your visor's
making a difference.

333
00:21:20,154 --> 00:21:22,281
It's making a difference all right.

334
00:21:22,364 --> 00:21:25,409
No one's ever going to
see my face again.

335
00:21:25,493 --> 00:21:28,871
-Can I get you anything?
-An old age would be nice.

336
00:21:29,997 --> 00:21:33,000
-Anything you can do?
-I'm all over it.

337
00:21:33,083 --> 00:21:34,376
Doctor.

338
00:21:35,544 --> 00:21:37,588
When we first met you,

339
00:21:38,714 --> 00:21:41,592
you didn't trust Professor Song.

340
00:21:41,675 --> 00:21:45,262
And then she whispered a word
in your ear, and you did.

341
00:21:46,055 --> 00:21:48,390
My life so far,

342
00:21:48,516 --> 00:21:51,018
I could do with a word like that.

343
00:21:51,560 --> 00:21:53,229
What did she say?

344
00:21:55,397 --> 00:21:56,941
(ANITA CHUCKLES)

345
00:21:57,066 --> 00:22:00,861
Give a dead girl a break.
Your secrets are safe with me.

346
00:22:00,945 --> 00:22:02,988
-Safe.
-What?

347
00:22:05,282 --> 00:22:08,828
Safe. You don't say "saved".
Nobody says "saved”. You say "safe".

348
00:22:08,911 --> 00:22:10,538
The data fragment, what did it say?

349
00:22:10,621 --> 00:22:13,666
4,022 people saved. No survivors.

350
00:22:13,749 --> 00:22:15,042
Doctor?

351
00:22:16,502 --> 00:22:18,587
Nobody says "saved".
Nutters say "saved".

352
00:22:18,712 --> 00:22:21,423
You say "safe",
but it didn't mean safe, it meant...

353
00:22:21,549 --> 00:22:24,176
It literally meant saved!

354
00:22:26,804 --> 00:22:30,850
DONNA: What happened to your face?
EVANGELISTA: Transcription errors.

355
00:22:30,933 --> 00:22:34,520
Destroyed my face,
did wonders for my intellect.

356
00:22:34,603 --> 00:22:37,022
I'm a very poor copy of myself.

357
00:22:37,106 --> 00:22:41,026
Where are we?
Why are the children all the same?

358
00:22:41,110 --> 00:22:45,447
It's the same pattern over and over.
Saves an awful lot of space.

359
00:22:45,573 --> 00:22:47,074
DONNA: Space?

360
00:22:48,534 --> 00:22:50,244
EVANGELISTA: Cyberspace.

361
00:22:50,327 --> 00:22:52,454
No, don't tell! You mustn't tell!

362
00:22:53,455 --> 00:22:55,082
DOCTOR: See, there it is. Right there.

363
00:22:55,165 --> 00:22:58,210
100 years ago, massive power surge.
All the teleports going at once.

364
00:22:58,294 --> 00:23:00,838
Soon as the Vashta Nerada hit
their hatching cycle, they attack.

365
00:23:00,963 --> 00:23:03,549
Someone hits the alarm. The computer
tries to teleport everyone out.

366
00:23:03,632 --> 00:23:05,634
It tried to teleport 4,022 people?

367
00:23:05,759 --> 00:23:07,761
Succeeded, pulled them all out.
But then what?

368
00:23:07,845 --> 00:23:09,763
Nowhere to send them.
Nowhere safe in the whole library.

369
00:23:09,847 --> 00:23:11,557
Vashta Nerada growing in every shadow.

370
00:23:11,640 --> 00:23:14,602
4,022 people all beamed up
and nowhere to go.

371
00:23:14,685 --> 00:23:19,189
They're stuck in the system,
waiting to be sent, like emails.

372
00:23:19,273 --> 00:23:23,068
So, what's a computer to do?
What does a computer always do?

373
00:23:23,152 --> 00:23:24,737
It saved them.

374
00:23:28,282 --> 00:23:30,326
The library, a whole world of books.

375
00:23:30,409 --> 00:23:33,495
Right at the core,
the biggest hard drive in history.

376
00:23:33,579 --> 00:23:36,290
The index to everything ever written,
backup copies of every single book.

377
00:23:36,373 --> 00:23:39,460
The computer saved 4,022 people

378
00:23:39,543 --> 00:23:41,587
the only way a computer can.

379
00:23:41,670 --> 00:23:44,423
It saved them to the hard drive.

380
00:23:45,215 --> 00:23:47,593
EVANGELISTA: Your physical self
is stored in the library

381
00:23:47,676 --> 00:23:49,219
as an energy signature.

382
00:23:49,303 --> 00:23:52,932
It can be actualised again
whenever you or the library requires.

383
00:23:53,015 --> 00:23:54,516
The library?

384
00:23:56,352 --> 00:23:58,771
If my face ends up
on one of those statues...

385
00:23:58,854 --> 00:24:00,981
You remember the statues?

386
00:24:03,108 --> 00:24:07,237
Wait. No. Just hang on. So...

387
00:24:08,322 --> 00:24:11,575
This isn't the real me.
This isn't my real body.

388
00:24:12,409 --> 00:24:14,078
I've been dieting!

389
00:24:14,203 --> 00:24:17,873
What you see around you,
this entire world,

390
00:24:17,998 --> 00:24:20,709
is nothing more than virtual reality.

391
00:24:23,963 --> 00:24:26,131
So why do you look like that?

392
00:24:26,215 --> 00:24:31,261
I had no choice. You teleported,
you're a perfect reproduction.

393
00:24:31,345 --> 00:24:36,767
I was just a data-ghost caught in
the Wi-Fi and automatically uploaded.

394
00:24:36,892 --> 00:24:40,896
-And it made you clever?
-We're only strings of numbers in here.

395
00:24:40,980 --> 00:24:44,149
I think a decimal point
may have shifted in my IQ.

396
00:24:44,233 --> 00:24:47,444
But my face has been
the bigger advantage.

397
00:24:47,569 --> 00:24:50,990
I have the two qualities you require
to see absolute truth.

398
00:24:51,073 --> 00:24:54,284
I am brilliant, and unloved.

399
00:24:57,579 --> 00:25:03,002
If this is all a dream,
whose dream is it?

400
00:25:03,085 --> 00:25:06,839
It's hard to see everything
in the data core, even for me, but...

401
00:25:06,922 --> 00:25:10,050
There is a word. Just one word.

402
00:25:11,802 --> 00:25:12,928
CAL.

403
00:25:17,599 --> 00:25:19,768
ELLA: Mummy, my knee!

404
00:25:19,893 --> 00:25:25,190
Oh! Oh, look at that knee.
Oh, look at that silly knee.

405
00:25:25,274 --> 00:25:28,444
She's not real. They're fictions.

406
00:25:28,527 --> 00:25:32,322
I'm sorry, but now that you understand
that, you won't be able to keep a hold.

407
00:25:32,406 --> 00:25:34,783
They are sustained only by your belief.

408
00:25:34,867 --> 00:25:36,618
You don't know, you don't have children.

409
00:25:36,702 --> 00:25:38,287
Neither do you.

410
00:25:40,164 --> 00:25:43,709
Donna, for your own sake, let them go.

411
00:25:43,792 --> 00:25:46,628
Stop it! You'll spoil everything!
I hate you!

412
00:25:46,795 --> 00:25:49,048
You're going to ruin everything!
Stop it!

413
00:25:49,131 --> 00:25:51,383
Sweetie, what's wrong?

414
00:25:51,467 --> 00:25:53,135
Shut up!

415
00:25:55,637 --> 00:25:57,806
Daddy! No, Daddy!

416
00:26:02,728 --> 00:26:05,230
(ALARM BLARING)

417
00:26:05,314 --> 00:26:07,566
What is it? What's wrong?

418
00:26:07,649 --> 00:26:11,612
ELECTRONIC VOICE: Auto destruct
enabled in 20 minutes.

419
00:26:13,280 --> 00:26:17,326
Mummy, what did the lady mean?
Are we not real?

420
00:26:18,452 --> 00:26:20,454
-Where are we going?
-Home.

421
00:26:21,663 --> 00:26:24,374
That was quick, wasn't it, Mummy?

422
00:26:24,458 --> 00:26:27,711
Mummy, what's wrong with the sky?

423
00:26:31,924 --> 00:26:33,425
What's maximum erasure?

424
00:26:33,509 --> 00:26:35,511
In 20 minutes,
this planet's gonna crack like an egg.

425
00:26:35,594 --> 00:26:39,098
No. No, it's all right.
The doctor moon will stop it.

426
00:26:39,181 --> 00:26:40,974
It's programmed to protect CAL.

427
00:26:41,058 --> 00:26:43,352
Now, you really
must stop this, you know.

428
00:26:43,435 --> 00:26:47,689
You've forgotten again, it was you
who saved all those people, haven't you?

429
00:26:47,773 --> 00:26:50,234
And then you remembered.

430
00:26:50,359 --> 00:26:52,820
Shut up, Dr Moon!

431
00:26:55,948 --> 00:26:58,367
No, no, no, no, no!

432
00:26:59,660 --> 00:27:03,080
ELECTRONIC VOICE: All library systems
are permanently offline.

433
00:27:03,205 --> 00:27:05,833
Sorry for any inconvenience...

434
00:27:05,916 --> 00:27:07,793
We need to stop this. We gotta save CAL!

435
00:27:07,876 --> 00:27:10,129
What is it? What is CAL?

436
00:27:10,212 --> 00:27:13,173
We need to get to the main computer.
I'll show you.

437
00:27:13,257 --> 00:27:18,011
-It's at the core of the planet?
-Well then, let's go.

438
00:27:25,561 --> 00:27:27,312
Gravity platform.

439
00:27:29,022 --> 00:27:32,067
-DOCTOR: I bet I like you.
-Oh, you do.

440
00:27:42,077 --> 00:27:44,413
Mummy, you're hurting my hand.

441
00:27:46,165 --> 00:27:49,668
You just stay where I can see you.

442
00:27:50,502 --> 00:27:52,838
You don't get out of my sight.

443
00:27:53,922 --> 00:27:55,507
Is it bedtime?

444
00:28:05,058 --> 00:28:09,855
Okay. That was lovely, wasn't it?

445
00:28:09,938 --> 00:28:11,773
That was a lovely bedtime.

446
00:28:11,899 --> 00:28:15,444
We had warm milk,
and we watched cartoons.

447
00:28:15,527 --> 00:28:19,323
And then Mummy read you
a lovely bedtime story.

448
00:28:19,448 --> 00:28:23,660
Mummy, Joshua and me,
we're not real, are we?

449
00:28:23,785 --> 00:28:27,247
Of course you're real.
You're as real as anything.

450
00:28:28,248 --> 00:28:30,000
Why do you say that?

451
00:28:30,125 --> 00:28:35,130
But, Mummy, sometimes when you're
not here, it's like we're not here.

452
00:28:35,214 --> 00:28:39,134
Even when you close your eyes,
we just stop.

453
00:28:40,844 --> 00:28:45,682
Well, Mummy promises to
never close her eyes again.

454
00:28:54,566 --> 00:28:56,151
No. No...

455
00:28:57,861 --> 00:29:01,490
No, please! No, please!

456
00:29:02,741 --> 00:29:05,994
(SCREAMING) No! No!

457
00:29:07,246 --> 00:29:09,122
No!

458
00:29:09,790 --> 00:29:10,874
No!

459
00:29:10,999 --> 00:29:13,460
(SOBBING HYSTERICALLY)

460
00:29:14,503 --> 00:29:18,215
ELECTRONIC VOICE:
Auto destruct in 15 minutes.

461
00:29:18,340 --> 00:29:22,219
The data core. Over 4,000 living minds
trapped inside it.

462
00:29:22,344 --> 00:29:26,014
Yeah, well, they won't be living
much longer. We're running out of time.

463
00:29:27,432 --> 00:29:32,479
Help me. Please help me.
Please, please help me.

464
00:29:38,694 --> 00:29:41,029
Help me. Please help me.

465
00:29:41,697 --> 00:29:45,701
-What's that? Was that a child?
-The computer's in sleep mode.

466
00:29:47,536 --> 00:29:48,870
I can't wake it up. I'm trying.

467
00:29:59,172 --> 00:30:02,718
-Doctor, these readings...
-I know. You'd think it was...

468
00:30:03,802 --> 00:30:07,097
-Dreaming.
-It is dreaming, of a normal life.

469
00:30:07,889 --> 00:30:11,143
And a lovely dad,
and of every book ever written.

470
00:30:11,977 --> 00:30:13,478
ANITA: Computers don't dream.

471
00:30:13,562 --> 00:30:16,273
Help me. Please help me.

472
00:30:16,356 --> 00:30:18,567
No, but little girls do.

473
00:30:30,746 --> 00:30:33,582
Please help me. Please help me.

474
00:30:33,665 --> 00:30:37,461
-Oh, my God.
-It's the little girl.

475
00:30:38,503 --> 00:30:42,758
-The girl we saw in the computer.
-LUX: She's not in the computer.

476
00:30:44,426 --> 00:30:48,597
In a way, she is the computer.
The main command node.

477
00:30:49,556 --> 00:30:51,016
This is CAL.

478
00:30:52,017 --> 00:30:53,935
CAL is a child!

479
00:30:54,019 --> 00:30:56,521
A child hooked up to a mainframe!
Why didn't you tell me this?

480
00:30:56,605 --> 00:31:00,108
-I needed to know this!
-Because she's family!

481
00:31:02,986 --> 00:31:04,404
CAL.

482
00:31:05,238 --> 00:31:07,157
Charlotte Abigail Lux.

483
00:31:08,617 --> 00:31:11,161
My grandfather's youngest daughter.

484
00:31:13,330 --> 00:31:18,794
She was dying, so we built her a library
and put her living mind inside.

485
00:31:19,836 --> 00:31:22,214
The moon to watch over her,

486
00:31:22,297 --> 00:31:24,132
and all of human history
to pass the time.

487
00:31:24,257 --> 00:31:27,094
Any era to live in. Any book to read.

488
00:31:28,095 --> 00:31:30,680
She loved books more than anything.

489
00:31:32,099 --> 00:31:34,518
And he gave her them all.

490
00:31:34,643 --> 00:31:37,813
He asked only that she be left in peace.
A secret.

491
00:31:39,898 --> 00:31:41,525
Not a freak show.

492
00:31:41,650 --> 00:31:45,570
So, you weren't protecting a patent.
You were protecting her.

493
00:31:49,074 --> 00:31:51,827
Hers was only half a life, of course.

494
00:31:53,412 --> 00:31:56,748
-But it's forever.
-And then the shadows came.

495
00:31:56,832 --> 00:32:01,253
The shadows. I have to...
I have to save...

496
00:32:03,046 --> 00:32:04,923
Have to save...

497
00:32:05,006 --> 00:32:07,426
And she saved them.

498
00:32:07,509 --> 00:32:10,053
She saved everyone in the library.

499
00:32:11,596 --> 00:32:14,307
Folded them into her dreams
and kept them safe.

500
00:32:14,391 --> 00:32:18,270
-ANITA: Then why didn't she tell us?
-Because she's forgotten.

501
00:32:18,353 --> 00:32:21,857
She's got over 4,000 living minds
chatting away inside her head.

502
00:32:21,982 --> 00:32:25,610
It must be like being, well...

503
00:32:25,694 --> 00:32:28,280
-Me.
-So what do we do?

504
00:32:28,363 --> 00:32:30,365
-Auto destruct in 10 minutes.
-Easy.

505
00:32:30,449 --> 00:32:32,284
Beam the people out of the data core.

506
00:32:32,367 --> 00:32:34,244
The computer will reset,
stop the countdown.

507
00:32:34,369 --> 00:32:37,372
Difficult. Charlotte doesn't have enough
memory space left to make the transfer.

508
00:32:37,497 --> 00:32:39,124
Easy. I'll hook myself
up to the computer.

509
00:32:39,207 --> 00:32:40,917
She can borrow my memory space.

510
00:32:41,042 --> 00:32:43,545
-Difficult. It'll kill you stone dead.
-Easy to criticise.

511
00:32:43,628 --> 00:32:45,797
It'll burn out both your hearts.
And don't think you'll regenerate!

512
00:32:45,881 --> 00:32:48,091
I'll try my hardest not to die.
Honestly, it's my main thing.

513
00:32:48,216 --> 00:32:49,843
-Doctor...
-I'm right, this'll work. Shut up.

514
00:32:49,926 --> 00:32:51,845
Listen, you and Lux
go back up to the main library.

515
00:32:51,928 --> 00:32:53,847
Prime any data cells you can find
for maximum download.

516
00:32:53,930 --> 00:32:55,348
And before you say anything else,

517
00:32:55,432 --> 00:32:58,185
can I just mention in passing,
as you're here, shut up!

518
00:32:58,268 --> 00:33:00,479
-I hate you sometimes!
-I know.

519
00:33:00,562 --> 00:33:04,316
Mr Lux, with me.
Anita, if he dies, I'll kill him!

520
00:33:05,525 --> 00:33:07,277
What about the Vashta Nerada?

521
00:33:07,360 --> 00:33:10,155
These are their forests. I'm gonna seal
Charlotte inside her little world,

522
00:33:10,238 --> 00:33:11,448
take everybody else away.

523
00:33:11,573 --> 00:33:14,075
The shadows can swarm
to their hearts' content.

524
00:33:14,201 --> 00:33:15,994
So you think
they're just gonna let us go?

525
00:33:16,077 --> 00:33:17,621
Best offer they're gonna get.

526
00:33:17,746 --> 00:33:20,081
-You're gonna make them an offer?
-They'd better take it.

527
00:33:20,165 --> 00:33:23,168
'Cause right now, I'm finding it very
hard to make any kind of offer at all.

528
00:33:23,251 --> 00:33:27,088
You know what? I really liked Anita.

529
00:33:27,214 --> 00:33:32,010
She was brave, even when she was crying,
and she never gave in, and you ate her.

530
00:33:33,929 --> 00:33:38,391
But I'm gonna let that pass,
just as long as you let them pass.

531
00:33:38,517 --> 00:33:41,770
-How long have you known?
-I counted the shadows.

532
00:33:43,480 --> 00:33:45,482
You only have one now.

533
00:33:48,026 --> 00:33:50,403
She's nearly gone. Be kind.

534
00:33:50,487 --> 00:33:53,615
These are our forests. We are not kind.

535
00:33:53,698 --> 00:33:57,619
I'm giving you back your forests,
but you are giving me them.

536
00:33:58,119 --> 00:33:59,412
You are letting them go.

537
00:33:59,496 --> 00:34:03,166
These are our forests.
They are our meat.

538
00:34:07,420 --> 00:34:10,465
Don't play games with me.

539
00:34:10,549 --> 00:34:14,511
You just killed someone I liked.
That is not a safe place to stand.

540
00:34:14,636 --> 00:34:18,848
I'm the Doctor, and you're in
the biggest library in the universe.

541
00:34:20,725 --> 00:34:22,143
Look me up.

542
00:34:34,364 --> 00:34:36,074
You have one day.

543
00:34:41,204 --> 00:34:42,289
Anita!

544
00:34:42,372 --> 00:34:45,500
I'm sorry, she's been dead a while now.
I told you to go.

545
00:34:45,584 --> 00:34:48,003
Lux can manage without me.

546
00:34:49,337 --> 00:34:50,839
But you can't.

547
00:34:55,594 --> 00:34:58,888
Auto destruct in two minutes.

548
00:35:03,226 --> 00:35:06,146
Oh, no. Come on, what are you doing?
That's my job.

549
00:35:06,229 --> 00:35:08,356
Oh, and I'm not allowed to
have a career, I suppose?

550
00:35:08,440 --> 00:35:11,151
Why are my hands...
Why do you even have handcuffs?

551
00:35:11,234 --> 00:35:12,319
Spoilers.

552
00:35:12,402 --> 00:35:14,988
This is not a joke. Stop this now.
This is gonna kill you.

553
00:35:15,071 --> 00:35:16,364
I'd have a chance. You don't have any.

554
00:35:16,448 --> 00:35:20,285
You wouldn't have a chance
and neither do I.

555
00:35:20,368 --> 00:35:22,120
I'm timing it for
the end of the countdown.

556
00:35:22,203 --> 00:35:23,622
There will be a blip
in the command flow.

557
00:35:23,705 --> 00:35:26,291
That way, it should improve our chances
of a clean download.

558
00:35:26,374 --> 00:35:27,626
River, please, no.

559
00:35:27,709 --> 00:35:32,130
Funny thing is, this means you've always
known how I was going to die.

560
00:35:32,213 --> 00:35:36,051
All the time we've been together,
you knew I was coming here.

561
00:35:36,134 --> 00:35:40,347
The last time I saw you, the real you,
the future you, I mean...

562
00:35:40,430 --> 00:35:44,392
You turned up on my doorstep
with a new haircut and a suit.

563
00:35:46,394 --> 00:35:49,814
You took me to Darillium
to see the singing towers.

564
00:35:51,608 --> 00:35:57,364
What a night that was!
The towers sang, and you cried.

565
00:35:58,323 --> 00:36:01,034
-Auto destruct in one minute.
-You wouldn't tell me why,

566
00:36:01,117 --> 00:36:04,579
but I suppose you knew
it was time. My time.

567
00:36:04,663 --> 00:36:07,540
Time to come to the library.

568
00:36:07,624 --> 00:36:11,711
You even gave me your screwdriver.
That should have been a clue.

569
00:36:11,795 --> 00:36:15,590
-There's nothing you can do.
-You can let me do this!

570
00:36:15,715 --> 00:36:18,385
If you die here,
it'll mean I've never met you.

571
00:36:18,468 --> 00:36:21,012
-Time can be re-written.
-Not those times.

572
00:36:21,096 --> 00:36:23,431
Not one line. Don't you dare.

573
00:36:25,266 --> 00:36:29,396
It's okay. It's okay. It's not over
for you. You'll see me again.

574
00:36:30,897 --> 00:36:32,899
You've got all of that to come.

575
00:36:32,982 --> 00:36:36,111
You and me. Time and space.

576
00:36:37,737 --> 00:36:39,406
You watch us run.

577
00:36:41,533 --> 00:36:44,577
-River, you know my name.
-Auto destruct in...

578
00:36:44,661 --> 00:36:46,830
You whispered my name in my ear.

579
00:36:46,955 --> 00:36:50,083
...ten, nine, eight, seven...

580
00:36:50,166 --> 00:36:53,962
There's only one reason
I would ever tell anyone my name.

581
00:36:54,087 --> 00:36:57,006
-There's only one time I could.
-Hush now.

582
00:36:57,966 --> 00:37:00,009
-...three...
-Spoilers.

583
00:37:00,093 --> 00:37:02,303
...two, one.

584
00:37:09,352 --> 00:37:12,063
Donna! What's happening?

585
00:37:13,148 --> 00:37:15,400
I don't know, but it's not real.

586
00:37:15,483 --> 00:37:19,946
Nothing here is real. The whole world.
Everything. None of it is real.

587
00:37:21,030 --> 00:37:22,449
Am I real?

588
00:37:23,658 --> 00:37:25,577
Of course you're real.

589
00:37:26,202 --> 00:37:27,996
I know you're real.

590
00:37:28,997 --> 00:37:32,584
Oh, God! Oh, God! You were real!

591
00:37:32,667 --> 00:37:34,461
(STAMMERING)

592
00:37:38,423 --> 00:37:42,844
I'll find you.
I promise you, I'll find you.

593
00:37:50,977 --> 00:37:52,520
MAN: Excuse me.

594
00:37:54,189 --> 00:37:57,108
What happened? How did we get here?

595
00:37:58,777 --> 00:38:00,236
Look at you.

596
00:38:01,029 --> 00:38:02,530
You're back!

597
00:38:02,614 --> 00:38:05,325
You're all back. He did it!

598
00:38:05,408 --> 00:38:07,535
(LAUGHING)

599
00:38:07,619 --> 00:38:09,329
You're all back. Look at you.

600
00:38:22,425 --> 00:38:23,927
Look at that.

601
00:38:25,595 --> 00:38:27,680
Look at that, he did it.

602
00:38:28,723 --> 00:38:32,811
4,022 people saved.

603
00:38:56,626 --> 00:39:00,338
ELECTRONIC VOICE: Please be patient.
Only three can teleport at a time.

604
00:39:00,421 --> 00:39:04,175
Do not state your intended destination
until you arrive...

605
00:39:04,259 --> 00:39:05,969
Any luck?

606
00:39:07,804 --> 00:39:11,683
There wasn't even anyone called Lee
in the library that day.

607
00:39:11,766 --> 00:39:15,019
I suppose he could have had
a different name out here, but...

608
00:39:15,103 --> 00:39:19,065
Let's be honest, he wasn't real, was he?

609
00:39:20,024 --> 00:39:21,442
Maybe not.

610
00:39:23,111 --> 00:39:25,446
I made up the perfect man.

611
00:39:25,572 --> 00:39:29,450
Gorgeous, adores me,
and hardly able to speak a word.

612
00:39:30,201 --> 00:39:32,912
-What does that say about me?
-Everything.

613
00:39:33,955 --> 00:39:36,457
Sorry, did I say "everything"?
I meant to say "nothing".

614
00:39:36,541 --> 00:39:40,003
I was aiming for "nothing”,
I accidentally said "everything".

615
00:39:40,128 --> 00:39:43,381
Stand right in the middle
of the teleport, please. Keep your...

616
00:39:43,464 --> 00:39:47,635
What about you? You all right?

617
00:39:47,719 --> 00:39:49,596
I'm always all right.

618
00:39:51,431 --> 00:39:57,270
Is "all right" special Time Lord code
for "really not all right at all"?

619
00:39:57,937 --> 00:39:59,147
Why?

620
00:40:00,398 --> 00:40:02,483
Because I'm all right, too.

621
00:40:08,072 --> 00:40:09,324
Come on.

622
00:40:36,142 --> 00:40:39,437
Your friend, Professor Song.

623
00:40:41,230 --> 00:40:44,776
She knew you in the future,
but she didn't know me.

624
00:40:44,859 --> 00:40:46,861
What happens to me?

625
00:40:46,986 --> 00:40:48,863
Because when she heard my name,
the way she looked at me...

626
00:40:48,947 --> 00:40:52,241
Donna. This is her diary.

627
00:40:55,703 --> 00:40:57,080
My future.

628
00:41:00,875 --> 00:41:02,961
I could look you up.

629
00:41:04,587 --> 00:41:06,547
What do you think?

630
00:41:08,174 --> 00:41:10,218
Shall we peek at the end?

631
00:41:17,517 --> 00:41:19,560
Spoilers, right?

632
00:41:21,062 --> 00:41:22,271
Right.

633
00:41:36,369 --> 00:41:38,162
Come on.

634
00:41:38,246 --> 00:41:40,498
The next chapter's this way.

635
00:41:42,750 --> 00:41:46,546
SONG: When you run with the Doctor,
it feels like it will never end.

636
00:41:46,629 --> 00:41:51,259
But however hard you try,
you can't run forever.

637
00:41:52,760 --> 00:41:55,513
Everybody knows that everybody dies.

638
00:41:55,596 --> 00:41:58,641
And nobody knows it like the Doctor.

639
00:41:58,766 --> 00:42:02,812
But I do think that
all the skies of all the worlds

640
00:42:02,937 --> 00:42:08,860
might just turn dark if he ever,
for one moment, accepted...

641
00:42:08,943 --> 00:42:12,989
Why? Why would I give her
my screwdriver? Why would I do that?

642
00:42:13,072 --> 00:42:15,033
Future me had years to think about it.

643
00:42:15,116 --> 00:42:16,909
All those years to think of
a way to save her.

644
00:42:16,993 --> 00:42:20,955
What he did was give her a screwdriver.
Why would I do that?

645
00:42:21,039 --> 00:42:24,459
Oh! Oh! Oh!

646
00:42:24,542 --> 00:42:28,087
Look at that! I'm very good!

647
00:42:28,171 --> 00:42:30,548
What have you done?

648
00:42:30,631 --> 00:42:32,633
Saved her.

649
00:42:38,598 --> 00:42:41,559
Stay with me. You can do it.
Stay with me. Come on.

650
00:42:41,642 --> 00:42:43,728
You and me, one last run.

651
00:42:48,524 --> 00:42:50,777
Sorry, River. Shortcut.

652
00:42:51,652 --> 00:42:54,280
Platform disabled.

653
00:43:03,581 --> 00:43:06,584
SONG: Everybody knows
that everybody dies.

654
00:43:09,837 --> 00:43:11,631
But not every day.

655
00:43:14,509 --> 00:43:15,843
Not today.

656
00:43:41,160 --> 00:43:44,080
CAL: It's okay. You're safe.

657
00:43:44,163 --> 00:43:46,124
You'll always be safe here.

658
00:43:46,207 --> 00:43:50,294
The Doctor fixed the data core.
This is a good place now.

659
00:43:50,378 --> 00:43:54,382
But I was worried you might be lonely,
so I brought you some friends.

660
00:43:54,465 --> 00:43:56,342
Aren't I a clever girl?

661
00:43:56,425 --> 00:43:58,302
Aren't we all?

662
00:44:02,348 --> 00:44:04,517
Oh, for heaven's sake.

663
00:44:04,600 --> 00:44:07,520
He just can't do it, can he?

664
00:44:07,603 --> 00:44:10,356
That man. That impossible man.

665
00:44:12,900 --> 00:44:14,902
He just can't give in.

666
00:44:33,171 --> 00:44:35,506
SONG: Some days are special.

667
00:44:35,590 --> 00:44:38,593
Some days are so, so blessed.

668
00:44:40,344 --> 00:44:42,680
Some days, nobody dies at all.

669
00:45:10,958 --> 00:45:15,171
Now and then,
every once in a very long while,

670
00:45:15,254 --> 00:45:19,091
every day in a million days
when the wind stands fair

671
00:45:19,175 --> 00:45:21,469
and the Doctor comes to call...

672
00:45:26,599 --> 00:45:28,601
everybody lives.

673
00:45:59,840 --> 00:46:01,801
Sweet dreams, everyone.

674
00:46:09,850 --> 00:46:11,769
-You be careful.
-DOCTOR: Taking a big space truck

675
00:46:11,852 --> 00:46:14,480
with a bunch of strangers
across a diamond planet called Midnight?

676
00:46:14,563 --> 00:46:15,773
What could possibly go wrong?

677
00:46:15,856 --> 00:46:18,567
-Enjoy your trip.
-Oh, I can't wait.

678
00:46:18,651 --> 00:46:20,945
What the hell is making that noise?

679
00:46:21,028 --> 00:46:23,698
-It's trying the door!
-There is no "it".

680
00:46:23,781 --> 00:46:24,824
(LOUD BANGING)

681
00:46:24,907 --> 00:46:26,784
Just tell me what the hell it is!

682
00:46:26,867 --> 00:46:27,952
Down!

683
00:46:28,035 --> 00:46:30,371
If we're gonna get out of this,
then you need me.

684
00:46:30,454 --> 00:46:31,747
Oh, like you're so special.

685
00:46:31,831 --> 00:46:35,084
-Two people are dead.
-Don't make it a third.

686
00:46:35,418 --> 00:46:38,921
It's coming for me.
It's coming for me. Help!

687
00:46:39,880 --> 00:46:41,007
Get out of there!

